An '''Obscene temple''' is a temple{{Efn|[[Ci shrine|Ci]][[Miao shrine|miao]]}} where [[Obscene sacrifice|Obscene sacrifices]] are performed<ref>[[俞正燮]]《[[癸巳类稿]]·非无鬼》：“北有野祭，南或淫祠，是天之下，地之上，皆明鬼者也。” </ref>。The [[Book of Rites]] condemns Obscene temples and [[Obscene sacrifice]].<ref>《聖祖實錄·康熙九年癸巳條》</ref>

==Overview==

'''Extraneous Shrine''' (淫祠) refers to shrines not officially sanctioned by state rituals, which are mostly self-established by the people as {{ill|Shrine|de|Schrein|ja|祠庙|zh|祠庙}}. <ref>{{ill|Yu Zhengxie|de|Yu Zhengxie|ja|俞正燮|zh|俞正燮}}’s ‘’{{ill|Guisi Leigao|de|Guisi Leigao|ja|癸巳类稿|zh|癸巳类稿}} · Not Without Ghosts’’ states: “In the north, there are wild sacrifices; in the south, there may be extraneous shrines—beneath the heavens and above the earth, all ghosts are manifest.”</ref>.

The term “extraneous” here implies redundancy; an extraneous shrine is an unnecessary shrine, which typically results in a waste of labor and resources. The ‘’{{ill|Book of Rites|de|Das Buch der Riten|ja|禮記|zh|禮記}} · Qu Li Xia’’ clearly states: “To sacrifice that which is not one’s designated deity is called extraneous worship; extraneous worship brings no fortune.” The ‘’{{ill|Song Shu|de|Song-Buch|ja|宋书|zh|宋书}} · Record of Emperor Wu, Part II’’ declares: “Extraneous shrines deceive the people and squander wealth; as mandated by earlier regulations, they should be abolished along with all such temples.”

During the Tang dynasty, acts of demolishing extraneous shrines were common. The ‘’{{ill|New Book of Tang|de|Neues Buch der Tang|ja|新唐书|zh|新唐书}} · Biography of Di Renjie’’ records: “In the customs of Wu and Chu, extraneous shrines were abundant; once Di Renjie prohibited them, a total of 1,700 shrines were demolished, leaving only the four shrines dedicated to Xia Yu, Wu Taibo, Ji Za, and Wu Yuan.”

In the Song dynasty, {{ill|Chen Xiliang|de|Chen Xiliang|ja|陳希亮|zh|陳希亮}} also carried out the demolition of extraneous shrines. {{ill|Fan Zhen|de|Fan Zhen|ja|范镇|zh|范镇}}’s ‘’Dongzhai Jishi’’, Volume 3, records: “It is further known that in Yudu County of Qianzhou, several hundred extraneous shrines were demolished, and over seventy families of shamans were compelled to register as respectable citizens.”

==See also==
* {{ill|Extraneous Worship|de|Überflüssige Verehrung|ja|淫祀|zh|淫祀}}
* {{ill|Chinese Folk Religion|de|Chinesischer Volksglaube|ja|中國民間信仰|zh|中國民間信仰}}
* {{ill|Religious Freedom|de|Religionsfreiheit|ja|宗教自由|zh|宗教自由}}

